Here is a Java implementation of a quicksort algorithm with a counter for comparisons, with test cases:

```java
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.Comparator;

public class QuickSort<T extends Comparable<T>> {
    private int comparisonCount = 0;
    private Comparator<T> comparator = Comparator.naturalOrder();

    public void sort(T[] array) {
        if (array == null || array.length == 0) return;

        quicksort(array, 0, array.length - 1);
    }

    private void quicksort(T[] array, int left, int right) {
        if (left < right) {
            int partitionIndex = partition(array, left, right);
            quicksort(array, left, partitionIndex - 1);
            quicksort(array, partitionIndex + 1, right);
        }
    }

    private int partition(T[] array, int left, int right) {
        // Choosing pivot as the middle element
        T pivot = array[left + (right - left) / 2];
        int i = left, j = right;
        while (i <= j) {
            while (compare(array[i], pivot) < 0) {
                i++;
            }
            while (compare(array[j], pivot) > 0) {
                j--;
            }
            if (i <= j) {
                swap(array, i, j);
                i++;
                j--;
            }
        }
        return i;
    }

    private int compare(T a, T b) {
        comparisonCount++;
        return comparator.compare(a, b);
    }

    private void swap(T[] array, int i, int j) {
        T temp = array[i];
        array[i] = array[j];
        array[j] = temp;
    }

    public int getComparisonCount() {
        return this.comparisonCount;
    }
}

// Test Cases
public class QuickSortTest {
    @Test
     public void testIntegers() {
         QuickSort<Integer> quickSort = new QuickSort<Integer>();
         Integer[] array = {1,5,2,6,3,7};

         quickSort.sort(array);

         Assert.assertEquals("Array should be sorted:", new Integer[]{1,2,3,5,6,7}, array);
     }

     @Test
     public void testStrings() {
         QuickSort<String> quickSort = new QuickSort<String>();
         String[] array = {"dog","cat","mouse","elephant","tiger","lion"};

         quickSort.sort(array);

         Assert.assertEquals("Array should be sorted:", new String[]{"cat","dog","elephant","lion","mouse","tiger"}, array);
     }
}
```

This program creates a generic QuickSort class where we keep track of comparisons via the "compare" function. 

Test cases include sorting integer and string arrays. Make sure that the test cases also cover the edge cases, such as sorting an already sorted array, an array sorted in descending order, and an array with identical elements. 

Please note that you need to have a testing library (like JUnit) in your classpath to run the tests. Adding more test cases for edge scenarios will be beneficial to ensure the robustness of the algorithm.

