Design a class in Java that serves as a basic calculator. This calculator should be able to perform addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, square root, modulus, and power operations on two floating-point numbers. 

In addition to performing these operations, the class should include an exception handling system to deal with erroneous input and division by zero. The class should also be able to handle incorrect input types and print an appropriate error message in such cases. 

Given below is a piece of erroneous code. Analyze it, identify the issues with it, and then proceed to write your own version.

```java
public class BasicCalculator {
    private double num1;
    private double num2;

    public BasicCalculator(double num1, double num2){
        this.num1 = num1;
        this.num2 = num2;
    }
    public double addition(){
        double add = num1 + num2;
        return add;
    }
    public double subtraction(){
        double minus = num1 - num2;
        return minus;
    }
    public double multiplication(){
        double mult = num1 * num2;
        return mult;
    }
    public double divison(){
        double div = num1 / num2;
        return div;
    }
    public double squareRoot(){
        double sq = Math.sqrt(num1);
        return sq;
    }
public BasicCalculator(String num1, String num2){
        this.num1 = Double.parseDouble(num1);
        this.num2 = Double.parseDouble(num2);
    }
}
``` 

- What are the problems with the given erroneous code?
- Demonstrate your understanding by designing an improved version of the BasicCalculator class.

output:
The problems with the given code are:

1. Typo in the method name divison(). It should be division().
2. No exception handling is provided for parsing errors in the constructor when input is in string format. If a string that can't be converted to a number is provided, the code will throw a runtime exception.
3. Division by zero isn't handled properly. If num2 is zero in the division method, we will get a math error for division by zero.
4. The squareRoot() method only operates on num1. It would be more flexible to allow the method to operate on either num1 or num2.
5. The modulus and power operations are not implemented.

The solution to the problem involves implementing error handling and modulus and power operations.

Here's the improved version of the BasicCalculator class:

```java
public class BasicCalculator {
    private double num1;
    private double num2;

    public BasicCalculator(double num1, double num2) {
        this.num1 = num1;
        this.num2 = num2;
    }

    public double addition() {
        return num1 + num2;
    }

    public double subtraction() {
        return num1 - num2;
    }

    public double multiplication() {
        return num1 * num2;
    }

    public double division() throws ArithmeticException {
        if (num2 == 0) {
            throw new ArithmeticException("Division by zero is not allowed");
        }
        return num1 / num2;
    }

    public double squareRoot(double num) {
        return Math.sqrt(num);
    }

    public double modulus() {
        return num1 % num2;
    }

    public double power() {
        return Math.pow(num1, num2);
    }

    public BasicCalculator(String num1, String num2) {
        try {
            this.num1 = Double.parseDouble(num1);
            this.num2 = Double.parseDouble(num2);
        } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Provided string cannot be parsed to a double");
        }
    }
}
```
In this improved version of the code, I've added the modulus and power functions. Additionally, I've implemented an exception handling system for division by zero errors and string parsing errors. Also, I've given the square root method the ability to operate on any number, not just num1.

